⚙️ Step-by-Step Setup
1️⃣ Install the free local AI library

Run this once:

npm install @xenova/transformers


This library downloads and runs pre-trained BERT-type models on your own CPU (no internet after setup).

2️⃣ Create a new file aiSpamDetectorLocal.js
// aiSpamDetectorLocal.js
import { pipeline } from '@xenova/transformers';

// Load once when app starts
let classifier;

async function loadModel() {
  if (!classifier) {
    console.log('🧠 Loading local spam detection model...');
    classifier = await pipeline('text-classification', 'Xenova/bert-base-multilingual-cased-sms-spam');
    console.log('✅ Model loaded');
  }
  return classifier;
}

export async function detectSpamAI(emailText) {
  const model = await loadModel();
  const result = await model(emailText);
  const label = result[0].label.toLowerCase();
  return label.includes('spam');
}


💡 The model "Xenova/bert-base-multilingual-cased-sms-spam" is free, small, and can detect spam messages well.

3️⃣ Use it in your IMAP client

If your Node.js uses CommonJS (require), convert imports like this:

// imapClient.js
const { simpleParser } = require('mailparser');
const db = require('./db');
const { detectSpamAI } = await import('./aiSpamDetectorLocal.js');


And when you parse each email:

const isSpam = await detectSpamAI(emailText);

4️⃣ What You Get

✅ 100% free — no API keys
✅ Fully automatic — no keywords, no manual steps
✅ AI-based — uses a real NLP model
✅ Runs locally — privacy-safe, no cloud dependency
✅ Works offline once model is downloaded

🧠 Optional: Speed Up

For faster inference:

npm install @xenova/transformers @xenova/onnxruntime-node


This allows CPU-level acceleration.

🧩 Bonus Tip

If you later want to train your own model for even higher accuracy, you can export labeled data from MySQL (spam/safe) and train it in Python for free with scikit-learn or transformers, then load it with @xenova/transformers.
